{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Motor Specification Analysis",
    "objective": "Synthesize the understanding of material properties versus circuit performance by correctly identifying and applying SI units for resistivity and impedance.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "When specifying components like motors, we must distinguish between the physical properties of the materials used and the overall electrical behavior of the completed circuit. For example, the copper used in the windings has a specific resistivity, while the entire motor winding provides a total opposition to alternating current known as impedance.",
      "Confusing these two quantities—or their units—can lead to incorrect cable sizing or motor selection."
    ],
    "questionText": "A technical data sheet for a motor lists two values: a material property of 0.0172 and a total AC opposition of 14.5. Identify which value is the 'Resistivity' and which is the 'Impedance', providing the correct SI unit symbol for each. Briefly explain why these two quantities use different units despite both being related to electrical opposition.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "0.0172 is Resistivity, measured in Ohm-metres (Ωm).",
      "14.5 is Impedance (Z), measured in Ohms (Ω).",
      "Resistivity is a property of the material itself (like copper), whereas Impedance is the total opposition of the specific circuit or component to AC flow, including resistance and reactance."
    ],
    "hint": "Remember that resistivity describes the metal itself (Ohm-metres), while impedance (Z) describes the total 'fight' against AC current in the finished motor (Ohms)."
  }
}

